author: @Pulsar77
text: An important caveat is that sets don't preserve order. So the elements of  newlist = list(set(oldlist))  can end up in a different order than in oldlist. If you want to remove duplicates from a list while preserving order, use an OrderedDict:  newlist = list(OrderedDict.fromkeys(oldlist).keys())  In Python 3.6 or later, you can simply use dict:  newlist = list(dict.fromkeys(oldlist).keys())
